text:
#metoo i'm not going to be apologetic for posting this because i feel that people don't understand the impact when someone carries emotional trauma around. when people touch you the wrong way,  relationships that get strained b/c of trauma, and the mental stress that causes someone to reflex on if everything that happened was their fault. .
i was sexually abused when i was 5 until i was 14 years old, mentally, physically, and emotionally abused by multiple different people. which is what contributed to my weight gain throughout my childhood.
.
i was oblivious to the world and how sick this world has become. we don't like to talk about uncomfortable things and don't really do anything about it. however, i can't keep silent.
.
i'm addressing this to the fighters that you're not alone. you are loved. you will be healed with time. you are vaild. i wish good blessings for your healing. #ibelieveher .
.
.
"believe that you can keep dreaming. i'm dreaming. it's still reality".

text:
police likely to invite cristiano ronaldo for questioning over las vegas rape claim, says american detective
#african
police likely to invite cristiano ronaldo for questioning over las vegas rape claim, says american detective juventus striker, cristiano ronaldo is likely to be invited by the police for questioning over his rape allegations asÂ detectives prepare to bring new methods to their investigation.Â the las vegas police have refused to reveal more details since after they had re-opened the case, but a us detective who haÂ handled 1,200 sexual assault cases said he had no doubt the force would want to question ronaldo over 34-year-old kathryn mayorgaâ€™s claims, at a time when the #metoo movement has triggered the re-opening of hundreds of historic allegations.Â according to the report by daily mail, ronaldoâ€™s alleged victim may be asked to undertake a new form of psychological assessment, designed to trigger memories of the night in june 2009 when she was with the footballer.Â the american detectives are reportedly finding increasing success in focusing on what they call â€˜neurobiological traumaâ€™, which allows those who allege sexual assault to recall details years later.Â ronaldo has repeatedly denied the rape allegations against him, but the court documents, first published by der spiegel, show that ronaldoâ€™s lawyers paid ms. mayorga, a teacher, $375,000 (Â£228,000) to maintain her silence on what happened in a bathroom at the palms hotel and casino in las vegas.Â it is understood that ronaldo maintains any sexual encounter between him and mayorga was entirely consensual.Â the post police likely to invite cristiano ronaldo for questioning over las vegas rape claim, says american detective appeared first on linda ikeji blog. source: linda

nadia murad has won the 2018 nobel peace prize.

ms murad did not just lose her mother in the genocide. she endured three months as a victim at the hands of is militants. she was bought and sold several times and subjected to sexual and physical abuse during her captivity.

after escaping, she became an activist, campaigning to help put an end to human trafficking and calling on the world to take a tougher line on rape as a weapon of war.

text: "months ago, i was very skeptical of the #metoo movement looking from the perspective of being a man and understanding how it negatively impacts and how there are certain situations that donâ€™t reflect where the man is wrong. or i didnâ€™t believe they were being honest. and some are being dishonest. but then i really had to sit back and think. thatâ€™s not the majority. i think as men we have grown up in the culture of sexual assault that we normalized. the small things we thought was nothing was really sexual assault, because we always had the upper hand. we never felt the pressure that these women were feeling. and when you really sit and take the time to think about how it must feel to be uncomfortable in a situation with someone who is stronger than you, who intimidates you, who is trying to make you do something they want, and you have this anxiety... as men we donâ€™t think about it. and we normalize it. we think she really wants it. these are things we have been taught. these are negative stereotypes weâ€™ve been taught. you have to do real self-reflection as a man. i think thatâ€™s what #metoo is doing. it's calling us to a higher self. and calling us to do real reflection and be able to take ownership and responsibility and be able to teach our sons what is the proper protocol for engaging with a woman...when you have these accusations and the credibility of a woman you have to ask what she stands to gain by coming out and lying on this man.  she has a family, her own children, sheâ€™s a professional woman. and to see her pretty much be going through the ringer and ridiculed after she had to deal with this trauma for years. and having the bravery to come forward. itâ€™s unfortunate. and it makes me as a man look in the mirror and want to be a better person and want my children to be better people." â€“ mc & activist @mysonnenygeneral of the @nyjusticeleague and @womensmarch on sex assault and protesting kavanaugh on episode 15 text:
a letter to all the girls. 
hello i hope you're having a nice day. i want you to know that you are enough. you don't need to base your self-esteem and self-worth on other people's opinions of you. you are your own judge. don't let anyone tell you who you are or what you are. don't let anyone tell you that you're too skinny or too fat, because truth is, you'll never please them, so be yourself. be beautiful. don't act dumb to be funny or to impress anyone, use the amazing brain you have and shock the whole world with how smart you are. i know it's not normalized for girls to be confident, butÂ be confident. when you think you look good, say it, "damn i look good." that's not arrogance, that's facts and it's confidence. also, just know you can hook up with whoever the fuck you want. don't letÂ anyone, especially boys, call you a whore or a slut for who you hook up with or how many times you do it. it's your body and your life, don't feel ashamed for doing what you want. if you feel anxious or scared, that's okay too. you're allowed to show weakness and you are allowed to not be happy all of the time. you are allowed to be human. don't change yourself for anyone, don't change yourself to please anyone but yourself. you are beautiful, and i believe in you. show everyone who you are, how strong you are. if you want to be an athlete, go for it. prove them wrong. if you fall, get back up and try again, because after all, you're a girl. fight like a girl, because girls fight strong. think like a girl, because girls are intelligent. be a girl because, we really rule.

don't letÂ anyoneÂ orÂ anythingÂ get in your way of being your best self.

text:
sending hugs to my sensitive souls and anyone dealing with triggers, especially right now. for anyone who works with the public, you being present and kind to others can be incredibly helpful however thankless it feels at times.
falling a bit behind on #queertoberâ€¦ left my art supplies in someone elseâ€™s car (old picture). but in the meantime, about almost having a panic attack in the grocery store during my work break earlier this week ğŸ™ƒâ€¦
. .(trigger warning)
.

i had gotten off the phone from a conversation that referenced other conversations about suicide and of course the cabinets in my brain flew open. i remembered someone saying â€œi couldn't imagine being so sad i wanted to kill myself!â€. to give some context, i was not suicidal but i was not mentally well when this statement was said (a few years ago). this was also about the time that i had literally moved as far away as i could from all the mental torment of sexual assault. the thing is, it comes with you, it gets bigger the longer you run. i would shower just so i could cry. i generally wasn't an enjoyable or stable person to be around and i would drink just to drown out the chest pains. .

my brain bounced back to the present, the recent past, and my past selves. kavanaugh, the #metoo movement,  the eyes of my friends and strangers as they relive the pain by telling their experiences.
.

my chest feels its about to break. my vision blurs. the dizziness set in and it feels like i'm going to throw up, pass out, or both. .
i stand in line and notice an acquaintance as the cashier and i'm reminded i should probably breathe. i go to their line. shaky and scattered as i was they don't flinch. they were their usual calm, soothing self. it made such a difference. you don't always have to have words or advice to give. sometimes just showing up and being present can make a big difference. thank you ğŸ’œ

text_retweet:
the nobel committee get it right! nadia murad wins the nobel peace prize!
##repost @unwomen @unwomensg ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
huge congratulations to 2018 #nobelpeaceprize laureate, nadia murad, who has been a brave and powerful voice for survivors of human trafficking and victims of sexual violence. in 2014, at the age of 19, murad was kidnapped in iraq, held hostage, and constantly subjected to sexual violence. after escaping 3 months of captivity, she started seeking justice for victims everywhere, telling her story to the world time and again, even though that meant reliving horrific memories of abuse and suffering. thank you nadia, for your courage to speak up and seek justice, not just for yourself, but for all survivors of sexual violence.
.
#nobelprize #endrapeinwar #nadiamurad #metoo

#nobelprize #endrapeinwar #nadiamurad #metoo

text:
we do what we like. don't read between the lines.
red is not an invitation. red is not a pigment of judgement. red is not regret. red is a preference. strong. bold. vibrant.
year 2007, grade 7: i felt afraid for i was pinched by a random man at a busy station. i almost cried, but i chose to walk up to him and slap him. 
i have been groped and molested in full public view. no one seemed to care, they watched in silence. people told me i shouldn't travel alone, i should be more careful. why advise me? how was that a fault of mine? 
my physics professor (@aakash institute) once asked if i could "fulfill his need" and that "he'd take care of mine," since his family lived in another city. you could, perhaps, make use of your hand, old man? another creep from the same institution stalked me for days...
at the gym i was going to, people spoke crap about me for helping a person who had nothing to eat. i am an extrovert, i talk to boys and girls alike. but there was character assassination... why? because of jealousy, stupidity, orthodoxy. 
many people blamed me for speaking up, for wearing what i wanted. they compared it with "cancer kinda feminism," a phrase i still don't understand. trust me, all this was when i didn't even have a red lipstick on. 
i was also being body shamed, was advised to lose weight to "look good" and cause they felt "clothes i wear would look better on me". when tells me what i should do, i do the exact opposite. those who know me well, will know this. 
stop victim blaming... say: i believe you, i hear you, i trust you, you're not alone instead â¤ï¸
@thenasty1, more power to you girl. 
#thegirlwiththeredlipstick #metoo #metooindia #metoomovement

the nationâ€™s largest legal organization is reopening its evaluation of supreme court nominee brett kavanaugh based on his performance during a senate hearing last week.

the american bar associationâ€™s standing committee on the federal judiciary said friday itâ€™s revisiting its evaluation based on â€œnew information of a material nature regarding temperament.â€ it said it was unlikely the process will conclude before the senate votes on kavanaughâ€™s nomination.

the aba was among the organizations that had called for an fbi investigation of allegations against kavanaugh. that probe was completed this week.

text:
to be a woman and truly belong in the world: nadia muradâ€™s nobel peace prize, one-year of #metoo and all the debate around shifting gender power-dynamics: my mind is in a flux! we are making some progress for sure - in terms of making this world a fairer place for women (essentially half-of-humanity, a fact which somehow tends to get lost). but the cost - oh the cost of this numbingly slow progress!
.
i have been reading a lot about nadia murad and dr. mukwege (joint recipients of the nobel). nadia muradâ€™s journey is harrowing and of inhuman courage: from being a prisoner-slave of is while her people were being systematically exterminated, to a lucky-escape, to recounting her painful experience to the world while holding on to the hope of justice. i hope she wins in her staggering battle against blatant genocide in the name of ideology (which i shall never understand). and every other woman - in her struggle, trivial or grand. we owe a fairer world to our children. [portraits from kumaon - 2, ramgarh, 28.09.2018]
.

.
.

text:
my form, like the earth below and the sky above deserves respect. all form is sacred, we are spirit inside these bodies and it is part of our work to cherish ourselves, respect one another, and all we see. 
for most of my life i have been running from my beauty showing it only in rare moments. my style evolved into a cross between a clown meets bag lady - but it didn't make anything easier. i was still denied, attacked, disrespected and #metoo'd even by the people i pulled in closest to my heart. as i continue to release my attachment to past stories and embrace this beautiful perfect now - i find myself reforming my relationship with my (aging) body putting it back in the water, swimming, moving, and inhabiting my light in the world. as i step into a fuller embodiment of my beauty i just wanted to give acknowledgement to the fullness capable in a notion of beauty. i am divine intelligence and goodness in a body - just like anyone reading this, just like you. we are all here, beautiful parts of it all. 
i move through these thoughts deeply touched by all the #cancelkavanaugh movements and the vote about to happen in the usa today. the moment bringing women into their bodies and into the streets claiming their voices and right to be seen. accepting the responsibility to create the change we want to see. 
as i sit by the ocean across the world this morning - i send my prayers out --- may all this pain and anger which have we inherited from unresolved distortion that have been passed across generations - passing from one angry hurt man and woman to another - may today be the day it is felt as seen - and in that witnessing from men and women around the world may the pain and anger find release. may this be the moment we go beyond pain without denying or hiding it - may we create a world where the light of our true beauty is safe to shine in it's fullest ability. may we live to experience the day where we see beyond and with our eyes and the sweet sound of truth in our voices of all are considered and heard by all. also, may the senators see clearly that a supreme court requires people that inspire peace and not divide.

"...life was supposed to return to normal for me as if nothing happened. i did not feel safe to talk about it at that time. in fact, i did not speak of the incident until many years later. as international day of the girl child approaches, i am in shame of living in a country where women and girls are neither respected nor celebrated.  where everyday we must fight for the equality and dignity of woman and the girl child.  i can relate to all the women in india going through any form of molestation in their everyday lives and keeping silent about it. this is only one of the innumerable encounters i have had with men who are hungry for a piece of us and have absolutely no regard nor respect for women. in my eyes, there are no laws and no system in place equally heinous enough in india to tackle this feat. i still live with the haunting traumas of past incidents.  as a woman, how long will it take before people take me seriously...." - debashree mitra (read her full story at pleasecheckmyblog.blogspot.com) -in case you didn't know it takes a huge amount of courage to share things like this! nothing but love for you debs! ğŸ’™â¤ï¸ğŸ’œğŸ’™) photo by sir @rahulzerg .

text:
funny, but so true. i heard it the other day, "oh, but you're a christian you can't, you're not supposed to." as if, one determines your limits to what you can or cannot say. to what you can or cannot hear, to what you can or cannot do. 
yeah, avoidance is better than entanglement, yet exposure is inevitable and many times i have conflicts of interests myself. 'if i'm gonna wear that christian name, as a soldier, i better change my ways or change my name.' this is true, not because i'm unsure of what's true and what isn't, but can't you see that i'm just like you?

still, i'm not conformed, we're being ... whaat? transformed... renewed.. day by day, observing the patters, yet i'm not ignorant of the devices it flows through. or is my ignorance towards the vanity of it all? what's being used, for what purpose and what's getting overlooked? although, perhaps over analyzing, there comes a moment when it's time to act. better be safe than sorry.

standing alone, but not moved by the crowd even though i'm pressured too. considering your views and comprehending where they stem from, i'm seeking solutions to draw parallels, are you? 
often dissatisfied and enjoy to be alone, not because i can't fit in, but in this unbiblical world view i simply just can't. there's free speech for thee but not for me so it's forced upon we the peeps, makes one want to go far, far away. catching myself daydreaming that one day i'll be off this planet, but i'm making sure that something is planted. a word of faith, a seed of truth. not just for #metoo but #you #too and i'm #voting #red
#sober #desiringgod #craving a #run or something as #fun close to #midnight

going on to the seventh month of #sobriety and i've gone mad!

i'm #grateful and enjoying this #journey i'll put down the mic #goodnight

text:
intercessor:
one willing to jump in a fight that has nothing to do with them. on behalf of god's ppl. 
true story: i thought when i got saved (12yrs ago) i would lose the "street keri" 
fact: he uses everything. he took a girl known to jump in a fight that had nothing to do with me & wreck havoc and turn those weapons into warfare. the drama in my life into the divine. and every stronghold into a strategy to beat the devil. i fight for my sisters. i contend for my friends.  god took the hell i went thru and used it to birth an intecessor out of me. i am godly grateful to be known as a woman of prayer in this hour. i prayed for std's tonight...in the room. i prayed for peninahs that have knowingly been the  cause of another woman's bitterness and i cried out for hannah's who have had to take that same bitterness to the lord in prayer. i prayed for deliverance from weed and perks... i have power over it because i have been delivered from it. aint no high like the most high god!!! i prayed for us who have passed the test of sex, drugs and cussing you out but carry hurt that has wounded us to the core. destructive thoughts that keep us from fully operating in ministry (because of misery) and for unforgiveness that keeps us replaying painful circumstances & memories. if any of these is you...know you're covered. i keri you #metoo i pray god deliver you from the need to see or seek revenge. i am not asking you to deny the severity of your wounds but give them to the one who was wounded for our transgressions. it doesn't absolve the guilty party. but it's insurance that when you stand guilty, and you will. you too will be forgiven. it frees your hands to receive healing. and blessings. there is power in the name of jesus. the more i call him...the better i feelğŸ™ŒğŸ¾ gn

text:
in november of 2015, i convinced two emt's that i needed to be taken to the hospital. they were convinced i was having a panic attack. they drove slowly, with the sirens off, and cracked jokes to (not with) my dad about how frequently they saw young girls getting worked up over nothing. 
i wrote this for a class over the summer, before brett kavanaugh was even named nominee. i can't bear to update it. i'm terrified of tomorrow. i'm terrified that my body is about to be illegal, that the voices of so many, too many, of the women in my life who have experienced much worse than i have really will be steamrolled over  because our government does not think they matter. we matter. this is not nothing. if you have had the courage and the bravery to post even a snippet of why this nomination will personally affect you over the past few weeks, i just wanted to tell you how much you are loved and how much your stories have resonated with me. thank you for still being here â¤ 
#metoo #susancollins #howdareyou #votethemout

text:
@regran_ed from @marcella.draws 
this.right.here. my sisters, we all feel it. our tears mingled, we slowly leave these last 2 weeks behind, fists slowly lowering. 
together we will rise, but now we rest.

we love ourselves a little more, hug our littles and our partners and our loved ones, we go to bed early perhaps. we indulge in self care because this is how we regain our strength to soldier on. 
we will fight the good fight, for ourselves, for the women who went before us, and for our daughters, nieces, and for generations of women to come.

it.is.not.over.

i love you all.

rest.

text:
on october 6, 2001, i was violated. when i reported it, rather than asking me how to help me or if i was ok, instead, they asked what i was wearing that night. i spoke out, yet this person continues to walk our public streets without ever having to serve a single day in jail. 
i wrote this song as part of my healing process and i am sharing it today as #1thing i can do to help those who have ever been victimized feel empowered to stand up for yourself no matter what, and know this - you are not alone. 
singing has literally saved my life and by sharing this song today, i hope it can save someone else as they find strength to heal. i am so incredibly grateful for the amazing continuous, unconditional love and support from my family and friends through this journey. *i chose to share this raw footage because thatâ€™s how real this is. we, as survivors, know the unimaginable nightmare of having your own power taken away, your world turned upside down, the gut wrenching pain your body endures in order to survive in a world where you no longer feel safe. those who have not experienced this devastation have no right to judge or make assumptions on how we should feel, the â€œappropriateâ€ amount of time to report it, or ask us â€œcanâ€™t you just get over it already?â€ instead, you can listen, show compassion, and take action as needed - we are here to support each other and lift each other up, not tear each other down. 
today, october 6, 2018, i am taking my power back and setting myself free. no longer a victim, i am a survivor and i will continue to speak my mind and stand up for what is right - i hope you will too. â€œunshaken, not stirred. not broken, but heard. fearless and reassured. i finally got the last word.â€ #nomore #timesup #metoo

singing has literally saved my life and by sharing this song today, i hope it can save someone else as they find strength to heal. i am so incredibly grateful for the amazing continuous, unconditional love and support from my family and friends through this journey. *i chose to share this raw footage because thatâ€™s how real this is. we, as survivors, know the unimaginable nightmare of having your own power taken away, your world turned upside down, the gut wrenching pain your body endures in order to survive in a world where you no longer feel safe. those who have not experienced this devastation have no right to judge or make assumptions on how we should feel, the â€œappropriateâ€ amount of time to report it, or ask us â€œcanâ€™t you just get over it already?â€ instead, you can listen, show compassion, and take action as needed - we are here to support each other and lift each other up, not tear each other down. 
today, october 6, 2018, i am taking my power back and setting myself free. no longer a victim, i am a survivor and i will continue to speak my mind and stand up for what is right - i hope you will too. â€œunshaken, not stirred. not broken, but heard. fearless and reassured. i finally got the last word.â€ #nomore #timesup #metoo

text:
iâ€™m a little late on the draw for national poetry day, but i wrote the following poem in honour of days that recognize and celebrate the power of words. the piece is certainly topical and inspired by current events. 
public servant: 
my bodyâ€™s public property 
not subject to its own sovereignty. 
serving me too, but not before you. 
it runs, walks, thinks bodily thoughts,
internalizes your ownership, 
confuses violence with love,
conflates sex with empowerment,
absorbs words of brutal meaning,
equivalent to physical beating,
berating and metaphorical raping.

my bodyâ€™s a public servant 
puts privileged rights over self service 
caring for me too, but not before you 
it protects your right to take from mine. 
itâ€™s judged, defamed, victimized and blamed,
twisted and slut shamed.
all to protect you from the risk of deserved pain,
from the first and forgotten time
when you took from me;
from the public domain of my body.  #poet #poetry #meta #body #mine #ibelieveher #himtoo #metoo #bodypolitics #poems #poetryofinstagram #metapoet #publicservant #topical #shitstorm

text:
the best nobel prize in a long time. 
25 year old gritty nadia murad has been awarded the 2018 nobel peace prize for her "efforts to end the use of sexual violence as a weapon of war". nadia murad survived the worst cruelties ever inflicted on her people, the yazidis of iraq, before becoming a global champion of their cause and winning the nobel peace prize.

the kurdish-speaking community follows an ancient religion, revering a single god and the "leader of the angels", represented by a peacock. during her ordeal, she was held captive and repeatedly gang-raped, tortured and beaten. she managed to cross to iraqi kurdistan, joining crowds of other displaced yazidis in camps. there, she learnt that six of her brothers and her mother had been killed. with the help of an organisation that assists yazidis, she joined her sister in germany, where she lives today. she has since dedicated herself to what she calls "our peoples' fight", even before the #metoo movement swept the world.

more power to you, resilient girl!

text:
had such an amazing sound experience at @woomcenter! 
there are so many things to do in new york city besides drink but i never explored them because i thought drinking was required on a trip to the big apple ğŸğŸ¸ tonight i sipped on hot tea and ate yummy sushi after this magical experience and will wake up sober with no regrets 
the first weekend i came to nyc sober i was so worried that i would not have fun and it had only been 8 months since i had stopped drinking. i was trying to save money and spent most of that weekend in parks, walked around the city in the day, got takeout and went to bed early. i also read books and really focused on staying sober 
now it's much easier to handle life and travel without drinking and i enjoy finding these cool experiences that create totally new and different memories in this beautiful city. 
they ended the experience singing ho'oponopono, an ancient hawaiian prayer used for healing, transformation and increased inner-peace and self-love. 
please forgive me.
i'm so sorry.
i love you.
thank you.

text:
the best nobel prize in a long time. 
25 year old gritty nadia murad has been awarded the 2018 nobel peace prize for her "efforts to end the use of sexual violence as a weapon of war". nadia murad survived the worst cruelties ever inflicted on her people, the yazidis of iraq, before becoming a global champion of their cause and winning the nobel peace prize.

the kurdish-speaking community follows an ancient religion, revering a single god and the "leader of the angels", represented by a peacock. during her ordeal, she was held captive and repeatedly gang-raped, tortured and beaten. she managed to cross to iraqi kurdistan, joining crowds of other displaced yazidis in camps. there, she learnt that six of her brothers and her mother had been killed. with the help of an organisation that assists yazidis, she joined her sister in germany, where she lives today. she has since dedicated herself to what she calls "our peoples' fight", even before the #metoo movement swept the world.

more power to you, resilient girl!

text: #ellendegeneres you use your platform for good, today you gave voice to how a great many of us feel and have felt. i was the freshman who was invited to homecoming by the senior homecoming king. he expected me to yield. i too was embarrassed during and after to fight back. i was so young and naive i tried to have a relationship with him afterward, he tossed me to his other friends as a piece heâ€™d already had. i was confused, a child of 15 myself. i didnâ€™t know what sex even meant other than i was supposed to â€œmarryâ€ the person i lost myself to. so innocent, such a victim of religious dogma and lack of parenting. scared to tell a soul i tried to move past what happened. it is still with me. i will not allow my daughter to undergo this grave great trauma. i guard her dignity with my life. thank you @theellenshow for your honest vulnerability. thank you #christineblaseyford for your courage.  #metoo #timesup #nomore

text:
@regran_ed from @belinda_vegan -  can you imagine, from the moment you open your eyes at birth, you are treated as nothing but a product?
the postal service delivers millions of packages, some of which contain live #animals. these #newborns will never be comforted by the warmest of their #mother.
_
most #ducklings/ #chickens purchased are bought from hatcheries or feed stores (feed store chicks originate from hatcheries). hatcheries ship day-old birds through the postal service without any legal oversight. young #chicks are deprived of food and water for up to 72 hours and exposed to extreme temperatures. as dr. jean cypher, a veterinarian specializing in avian medicine states, â€œa day-old chick can no more withstand three days in a #dark crowded box than can any other newborn.â€ other experts in avian medicine and behavior agree that transporting day-old chicks in boxes for the first 24-72 hours of life is cruel and medically detrimental to the birds. many of these chicks die from extreme temperatures.
_
sexing is done. separating the females from the males. it is estimated that between 20 and 50% or unwanted males end up on the streets. babies trying to survive!

male chickens/ducklings are generally unwanted for two reasons: they donâ€™t produce eggs and they are rarely legal in urban or suburban settings. hatcheries may use male chicks as packing material,(yes you read that right packing material), regardless of whether they were ordered. unwanted males may  be abandoned to the streets, slaughtered, or end up in a municipal shelter to be killed. very few find their way into a permanent home or sanctuary.
_
this is how animal agriculture treats babies. please stop participating in this. what if someone were shipping newborn #puppies and #kittens in a sealed box for 3 day, allowing many of them to die from the heat and cold the only difference is your perception.
embrace veganism ğŸŒ±

her
â€”â€”â€”
on the morning of thursday, september 27th, 2018, an eager anticipation woke us up in our brooklyn loft unusually early. with our hearts racing, we tuned into the hearings of dr. christine blasey ford and judge brett kavanaugh.
â€”â€”â€”
amidst dr. fordâ€™s emotionally brave testimony, kavanaughâ€™s flippant denial, and an amalgamation of statements from an assembly of both incredibly compassionate and unbelievably ruthless senators, we made a new song. and it was for her.
â€”â€”â€”
once the hearings were over, we began putting a video together to more fully capture the inspiration behind this song. we wanted to point to women, from a range of walks of life, women who have taken a stance when it wasnâ€™t necessarily easy to do so. our goal was to highlight the courage it takes to call something out loud and to stand up tall when the odds may not be in our favor.
â€”â€”â€”
the women in this piece are just a few among many who inspire us to continue to use our voices and demand to be heard. the conclusory chorus lyric â€œnever look back againâ€ doesnâ€™t imply we shouldnâ€™t look back on the women who have taught us how to lead the way â€” we most absolutely should â€” but that we should always move bravely into the future. we hope with our song to thank the women who have empowered us so selflessly and perhaps to inspire those still searching to find their strengths.
â€”â€”â€”
see the full video for â€œherâ€ now! link in bio.
â€”â€”â€”

text:
iâ€™ve been debating about sharing this since the â€œ#metooâ€ movement, but because of recently with everything going on iâ€™m saying screw it. 
i barely turned 14 and i was assaulted by a man who was a family friend, before i was even born, while staying at my brotherâ€™s. i was safe, i was in my own room with a door. i only woke up twice, once to him throwing a blanket back on me, and finally when i figured out what was going on. i cried, i cried so much. i was too afraid to even go back to sleep. i stayed awake until my sister-in-law woke up for her surgery. i couldnâ€™t even say what happened out loud. instead i should her a note i made on my phone. she made me go into my brotherâ€™s room and tell him what happened. 
i am one of the few who went to the police.

letâ€™s fast forward a year when i finally when to court.

after about 5 hours of being at the court house and testifying, i won. they found him guilty. and for once in that year i was relieved. until my family found out i wasnâ€™t the only victim. he also messed with another family member, and had also gone to court for him.

he was found guilty for two cases.

he was sentenced for five months of jail time for only me,because i was over the age of 13, however my other family member was 11. 
he got six months, or eleven months in total. 
he was released early for â€œgood behaviorâ€ 
both me and my family member were not informed by the court like we should have been when he was released.
i still see this man walking around town, but whatâ€™s even worse is that we arenâ€™t his only victims, and he was gone to court for them and still havenâ€™t seen a day in prison. 
listen to a woman in your life because honestly, they have a story. if you donâ€™t believe them or think â€œwhy didnâ€™t you tell soonerâ€ youâ€™re an asshole. ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ #metoo

text:
sometimes you don't realize how loud the silence is. how many times you've choked on the words. but i won't let you put your hands on my throat again. i won't keep your silence now.

my feed is gonna be a little intense for a bit, so i apologize in advance.
.
.
.
.
my silence felt so strong
until today
i thought i took away it's power
by pushing it away
by never
speaking it's name

my silence felt so strong
until today
when these hands began to raise
and i still felt ashamed
to stand with them
to give myself away

my silence felt so strong
until today
when my voice shook
when i tried to say
#metoo 
@amanda.x.coleman

#awareness #abuse #ptsd #poetry #writersofinstagram

she'll say i'm not your punchin' bag"
..."punchin' bag" - @cagetheelephant

i've been very quiet. too quiet, if you ask me. i've waited patiently, watching as our nation is faced with one of its most important decisions, hoping and praying for the right decision to be made. it saddens & sickens me to know it isn't so. 
to all of my sisters & brothers of the #metoo movement: do not let this discourage nor dampen progress. we have a fire inside us that will not be extinguished. 
to those of you who believe the #metoo  movement is a threat to your future by increasing your risk of being falsely accused of inappropriate sexual conduct, i ask that you kindly unfollow me because this is not the caliber of friends i wish to keep. based on my own life experiences and the experiences of countless men and women close to me who have fallen victim to sexual assault, these individuals are the real victims...not you and your ridiculous perceived threat against your honor and reputation. it repulses me that this conversation has been skewed so far in this direction. shame on you....shame on all of you. and if you think that commenting on this post will help you change my mind, save your time and energy. this is not up for debate. this is not something i take lightly. this is not something i will be swayed from. please unfollow me and move on. there's enough negativity in the world, i don't need more.

oh yeah, one more thing........ we're not your punchin bags

text:
@cabbiecat @time: "when dr. christine blasey ford walked in to face the senate judiciary committee on sept. 27, raised her right hand and swore to tell the truth, it was clear that an unassuming psychology professor and mother of two was about to change the course of current events in real time. â€œi am here today not because i want to be,â€ ford said to senators, who were prepared to assess her allegation that judge brett kavanaugh had sexually assaulted her some 36 years ago, a charge he vigorously denies. â€œi am terrified.â€ at stake was a potential lifetime appointment to the #supremecourt that could change decades of legal rulings and affect the nationâ€™s faith in its judiciary. the hopes and fears of #women and men who have lived with the trauma of sexual violence were riding on the credibility of fordâ€™s testimony. by the time the hearing ended, ford had done more than prove herself a credible witness. women called into c-span to tell their own, decades-old stories of harassment and rape. #whyididntreport exploded on social media, a rallying cry for those who had never gone public about their own sexual assault until then. fordâ€™s testimony slowed the machinery of political power when it was fully in gear. an npr/pbs newshour/marist poll released oct. 3 found that 45% of respondents thought ford was telling the truth, compared to 33% who believed kavanaugh. thatâ€™s a marked shift from 1991, when americans sided with clarence thomas after anita hill accused him of sexual harassment. the facts remain unsettled, and fordâ€™s testimony may not prevent kavanaughâ€™s confirmation. but it was a powerful warning that wealth, status and a record of professional accomplishments were no longer enough to override credible allegations of sexual assault, no matter when they occurred. to young #men, it was a message that drunken violence could shadow them. to victims, fordâ€™s testimony was an invitation to speak up, no matter how powerful the accused, no matter how long ago the attack. people will listen, the country seemed to reassure them. we will believe you.illustration by john mavroudis (@zenpop) for time; animation by @brobeldesign"

text:
i believe you. 
today, of all days, i needed to wear this shirt. my heart has been so heavy this past week. iâ€™ve seen my feed explode with #metoo stories. horrible stories. heartbreaking stories. true stories. .
tw: sexual assault
.
according to @rainn :
ğŸ˜¡an american is sexually assaulted every 9ï¸âƒ£8ï¸âƒ£ seconds. .
ğŸ˜¡every 8ï¸âƒ£ minutes, that person is a child. .
ğŸ˜¡1ï¸âƒ£ in 6ï¸âƒ£women is raped, or have experienced attempted rape. .
according to the hrc:
4ï¸âƒ£4ï¸âƒ£% of lesbians & 6ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£% of bisexual women experience rape, physical violence, or stalking by an intimate partner

2ï¸âƒ£6ï¸âƒ£% of gay men & 3ï¸âƒ£7ï¸âƒ£% of bisexual men experience rape, physical violence, or stalking by an intimate partner

4ï¸âƒ£0ï¸âƒ£% of gay men, 4ï¸âƒ£7ï¸âƒ£% of bisexual & 2ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£% of heterosexual men have experienced sexual violence other than rape
.
iâ€™ve always identified as a heterosexual white man. even in this body that hasnâ€™t always matched that identity. i didnâ€™t realize until recently how truly lucky i am to not be one of these statistics. iâ€™ve been reading and listening to stories from my friends that have been raped, drugged, jacked off on, touched at a young age, beaten, forced into oral sex, woken up at a party to find a boy/man hovering over them, pussy grabbed, fondled, kissed, shamed and the array of other terrible things a person should never have to endure, and i am heartbroken. we shouldnâ€™t make excuses for offenders. we should believe people, and uplift people when they are brave enough to share their most vulnerable and painful memories. .
to all my friends, to all those survivors, i believe you and i am so sorry that you were not respected and treated the way you deserve to be. i promise to use my voice and my status to role model what a man should be and how you, (man, woman, cis, trans, black, white, nonconforming, etc) should be treated.
.
you are believed. 
you are valid. 
you are not your experiences. .
@blofishclothing

text:
you are loved campaign 2018

every year i ask myself why.
why do i stay up late at night putting together information to help women's hearts heal? why do spend so much time talking on the phone or having meetings with women who i know may never pay me for mentoring or coaching them? exactly why do i continue year after year, buying gifts to put together these pink bags to hand  randomly to women? 
perhaps out of the 300, 500 or 1000 bags that are handed out, each year  i'm believing at lease one women's life may be saved from depression, suicide or an abusive relationship.

i do it  as an expression of god's love he gave me... john 3:16 Â for god expressed his love for the world in this way: he gave his only son so that whoever believes in him will not face everlasting destruction, but will have everlasting life.

yes, no matter what we may go through in life, all it may take to save a life for destruction, is a smile, a hug or perhaps a pink bag filled with candy, a hand written card, domestic violence community resources and the words "hello beautiful, you are loved" 
#metoo
#overcome #suicide #depression #childhoodmolestation #abuse #godsgirl #healedtoheal #empowertoempower #womenempowerment #sisterhood #empowerment #spiritualheartsurgeon #christiantransformation #lifecoach

text:
it's a tale of two nations.

it's the paradox i consider as i lull my son into drifting dream, whispers of magic and adventure and stars on his slowing breath. my lips still feel the gentleness of his down feather head, my nose still sensing the innocence clinging to his skin like radiant shrouds of light. he now shares his love without any prompting, and it is the voice of god.

i notice these things in the silence, when i pause just enough to listen and lose myself in wonder. it's how the sacred is found in the ordinary, to know that every moment holds significant, timeless weight. that boredom is when we convince ourselves that familiarity is certainty, when we assume that to know something means that we can no longer be surprised by it. that to know a thing is to have it figured out rather than to experience it anew.

i am able to ponder such truths because my wife is away for the weekend. though i'm writing about my son, this story is really about her. the only way i've been able to step back and behold my son tonight is because she's tirelessly, fiercely working and succeeding and providing for us.

perhaps more importantly than what she is doing for us, perhaps even more than how she's busting her ass and bearing multiple burdens so i, too can pursue my own dreams, perhaps more than the countless, restless hours spent poring over business plans and expense reports and network initiatives, 
perhaps more than all of this is what she's doing for herself.

she is empowered and strong and inspiring and independent and brave and confident and fearless. she is completely and utterly herself, and it is as sure and unpredictable and elusive as the wind now sharing secrets of the fall.

she gives without any thought of what she will gain in the transaction. she hopes without any regard for the resigned, sensible logic that holds so many victims hostage. she fashions grace from a spirit unyielding in its focus and desire and passion. she lives in such a way that she will leave nothing unattended, even as her body and health protest what her soul cannot deny.

so here i am, summer's skin cooling my own in its dying, receding day...**continued belowâ¬‡ï¸**

text:
"this is me..."
i'm not sure if i could say, sing, burst it out any more perfectly to express my position in all the political heat right now ...
my expression to you....i'm not scared to be seen, i make no apology, i hold sacred what i have created and i won't let you take it away from me. it is not possible. "i am not a stranger to the dark
hide away they say
cause we don't want your broken parts
i've learned to be ashamed of all my scars 
but i won't let them break me down to dust 
i know that there's a place for me 
for we are glorious
when the sharpest words wanna cut me down 
i'm gonna send a flood , gonna drown them out
i am brave i am bruised
i am who i'm meant to be 
this is me .
i'm not scared to be seen 
i make no apologies .... this is me. " .
.
.
. 
#thisisme #beseen #empowerment #womenspeakup #truth #metoo #healing #strongwomen #speakyourtruth

i was so young and happy. my life was full of excitement with high school graduation and being east coast college bound in the fall. i loved sports, poetry, my best friends and showing off my cute legs and midriff. and i was boy crazy. (is this where you start questioning my character?) i liked biceps in white t-shirts, abs and sandy blond hair. i was in cancun for graduation with my 2 best friends. we tanned our legs at the beach during the day and drank yard margaritas at night. (or maybe here?) our last night before heading home we stayed out late with all our new friends we made during the week. i donâ€™t remember where or how i ended up in a hotel hallway kissing one of them. (here certainly right?) i do remember i was in my favorite dress, it was blue and had yellow sunflowers on it paired with dr. scholes yellow clog flip flips. he was cute, tan from a week at the beach, brown hair, short-ish in height, and was wearing a button down shirt that was open exposing his shredded six pack. i donâ€™t remember how we got in the room, but i do remember being held my wrists onto the unmade bed. i was an athlete, so i was strong, so looking back i donâ€™t know how i couldnâ€™t stop it. did i not push hard enough? did i not yell? (this is where people that havenâ€™t experienced this donâ€™t understand.) i remember looking to one side staring at the wall with my eyes blinking back tears as i felt the weight of him on me and in me. i remember the smell of his boozy breath of those moments. itâ€™s why now, 18 years later, i canâ€™t stand to be kissed by unbrushed teeth. when it was over, as he lay on top of me, as i squirmed to pull my dress down he said, â€œthat was the best sex iâ€™ve ever had.â€ (who says that as an 18 year old kid? who says that to someone youâ€™ve been holding down for what felt like eternity?) i donâ€™t recall saying anything back or speaking at all as i left. (for sure here, youâ€™re thinking by now, you dumb girl.) with shaking legs i stumbled out of his room and stumbled past the front desk forgetting where my room was and crying silently. (you might be thinking, this is where she tells someone, the hotel security, the police.) nope. i didnâ€™t. not for a year.

text:
#believesurvivors #whyididntreport #metoo 
i was 15, i just thought we were hanging out.
i was 17, my friend had passed away and we were celebrating his life before the night drew on and everyone separated. i thought we were friends.

assault happens everywhere, these were the most extreme experiences for me, yet definitely not the first; and as scary as it is, i won't be surprised if they're not the last.
because it is not my fault. i did things and put myself in the situation, yes. i did not tell them to overpower me or take advantage. you don't have to fight back to be validated, people freeze- and it's more natural than fight or flight. 
blaming survivors only excuses their predator.

i was 17, my friend had passed away and we were celebrating his life before the night drew on and everyone separated. i thought we were friends.

assault happens everywhere, these were the most extreme experiences for me, yet definitely not the first; and as scary as it is, i will not be surprised if they're not the last.
because it is not my fault. i did things and put myself in the situation, yes. i did not tell them to overpower me or take advantage. you do not have to fight back to be validated, people freeze- and it is more natural than fight or flight. 
blaming survivors only excuses their predator.

text:
y'all, today is hard. pregnancy headaches that won't let up, second trimester nausea (less frequent but more severe than the first), tired from a long run of rehearsals, and the news is hard.
 trying to stay engaged, but also take care of myself. current events are bringing up a lot of personal stuff and really making me question what we as a society can do for women survivors to trust that if they come forward, they will be heard.
decided to hit the mat to work a good sweat, but couldn't muster my normal gusto today (despite what it might look like in a time lapse-- this was an hour long practice). a slower, more restorative practice was the way to go. needed to move, but also needed a second of stillness to listen to my inner wisdom. don't feel guilty about taking a step back when you need to. listen to your body, listen to your heart. you're wiser than you think. â™¥ï¸ #listentoyourbody #pregnantaf #pregnantyoga #metoo #yogaeverydamnday @theelephantpants

ğŸ–¤my stories of domestic violence including physical, verbal, and psychological abuse (occurring with my father and 2 husbands)...sexual abuse, sexual assault; sexual harrassment.. span my lifetime...from a grandfather, another family member, bosses, doctors, "friends"; to even a teacher of one of my kids.  some were reported...most were not. the reporting and subsequent victim-blaming which ensued added heavy layers of trauma to an already shattered self  you know the outcome of reporting.  when i worked in a law office in my mid twenties. it was a regular occurrence, even over the phone.

.
.
.

i went to law school because i saw my counseling clients with disabilities being mistreated by police, schools, lawyers, coworkers, landlords, romantic partners, and employers. i grew tired pretty quickly of referring clients to lawyers who had zero knowledge on disability, and then having to train the lawyers on how disability can affect a person and the law. i saw a problem and wanted to be an agent for change
.
.
.

you can do it too. all you have to do is find a constructive way to channel  your anger, frustration, goals, and ambition. ask around, find a mentor, do your research or find a good rehab/career counselor to guide you in the right direction...i know a great one ğŸ™‹ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸
.
.
.

text:
woman. she will not be cast into the shadows. woman. strong. fierce. true. magical. beautiful. intelligent. mystical. resilient. powerful.
___
in 2006, i brought forward my â€œme tooâ€ case with my employer. i didnâ€™t want to, and convinced myself the assault was my fault and i should stay quiet.  i was full of shame, and only made a report, months later, at the encouragement of my mentor at the time. like the stories of many women i hear in my coaching practice, i had assumed i had done something wrong for such a situation to happen. the perpetrator was a person of power within the organization, and i thought for sure my complaint would be dismissed - moreover, i could be terminated for creating â€œtrouble.â€ at the time, such was the landscape of my mind - steeped in conditioning of â€œbeing good/quiet,â€ mistrust in myself and my abilities to articulate what is true, and lack of conviction in my own abilities. i felt most safe, while largely unconsciously, people-pleasing, self-doubting, and second-guessing my instincts. even though these mentalities brought me discomfort, i found a false sense of security within their confines.
___
to my great surprise, an internal investigation was held upon my bringing the situation forward, and this individual was ultimately asked to leave the company. the empowerment and support i felt from this unexpected outcome was indescribable.
___
i canâ€™t imagine bringing forward my case, before millions of people televised, to be met with mocking and scorn by the president of the united states.  to be told i was a liar and sham. my blood has been boiling, and the anger is acute.  there is also a clear resiliency that is crystallizing within me, in response to this heavy outrage.
___
no, this is not ok.  no, we will not be quiet and let this â€œgo by.â€ yes, we are pushing back on the belittlement, misogyny, racism, and hate that is being projected from those at top.
___
i am grateful for the woman i am today, who has grown a lot from the fearful girl in 2006. this younger version is still a part of me, and there is also an inner strength, which is now activated. she knows she has a right to have a voice. (complete in comments ğŸ‘‡ğŸ»)

text: iâ€™m tired and iâ€™m heartbroken but i love us. i saw many women dressed completely in black today. it gave me hope in a time of darkness. a lot has been stirring for me lately. i think most people have no idea what sexual abuse does to a person. iâ€™m still discovering that after a childhood filled with it. the roots run deep. iâ€™ve unearthed clarities about my experiences that wouldnâ€™t have come without the voice of dr. ford. mostly iâ€™ve always dealt with my abuse in the safety of my counselorâ€™s office, a friendâ€™s trust or my husbandâ€™s unwavering devotion. there others who are standing up and saying that we are done, that our voices will no longer be silenced. to hear the backlash and taunting, the mockery and pushback is painful but extremely familiar. i text: cw: disussion of sexual assault. it's been a rough couple of weeks for me. i've been trying to limit social media as a means of self-care. seeing dr. christine blasey ford's courageous testimony, and the horrible reactions from people, has been heartbreaking and triggering for me, and brought up a lot of unpleasant memories. i was sexually abused by my father throughout my childhood, and in my teen years i was sexually assaulted more than once. i didn't tell anyone because i didn't know that some of what happened to me was assault. i had never heard of date rape. i'm realizing that i haven't ever really dealt with most of those memories that had been repressed, and consequently with the emotions that go along with them. i've been a mess emotionally, trying to make sure i stay grounded in the present. i know it's rough for a lot of rape and assault survivors- but remember, we are strong, and we already survived the abuse. we can survive dealing with the pain and emotions, and we will come out the other side even stronger. #ptsd #depression #anxiety #childsexualabusesurvivor #iamasurvivor #whyididntreport  #metoo #istandwithdrford  #believesurvivors #believewomen #courage #strength #istandwithsurvivors #ibelieveyou #nomeansno #wearestrong #alwayskeepfighting

iâ€™m beyond furious at senator susan collins decision  to betray her nation, survivors of sexual assault and women this afternoon by loaning her power to a candidate so clearly unqualified by both his temperament and his inclination to dishonesty to be a supreme court judge. 
collins damning assessment of dr. fordâ€™s allegations - claiming to â€œbelieveâ€ her while simultaneously claiming her recollection is suspect, is egregiously sexist and patronizing.
so many women are raised to mistrust and disbelieve other women. think about it, female inferiority is a tenet of all major monotheistic (and certain polytheistic) religions. anyone who calls themselves â€œconservativeâ€ or ascribes to traditional, abrahamic religious beliefs will be indoctrinated from birth to believe women are not equal to men in any capacity.
 iâ€™m fairly certain she was made to believe from an early age that women are inferior to men, or possess â€œinferiorâ€ characteristics. regardless of her success or lip service to being supportive of womenâ€™s lived experience, her programmed default is sympathy for and trust in, men (specifically white men) before women. .
misogyny is insidious in our society. even other women adhere to the â€œtrust no bitchâ€ mythos of it. 
so i suggest that all of us who believe in â€œsisterhoodâ€ start walking the walk, even more. 
now is the time to extend some trust and kindness to women you donâ€™t know. donâ€™t fall prey to competing for male approval or undermining each other for the crumbs tossed to us by the patriarchy. start supporting women owned businesses, especially single proprietorships. help other women by sharing opportunities and resources. give each other the benefit of the doubt. speak out when men are sexist and if they are men you care for, take a moment to tell them how and why that bullshit ruins their lives too. and for fucks sake, stop reinforcing the patriarchal narrative by referring to male weakness or weakness in general with the word, â€œbitchâ€. just stop it.

text:
twenty years old,
â€œyou are beautiful,â€ he told me,
but how could he know if all he ever saw was my body, never my heart?
.
a curious mind drove me to explore the unseen edges:
â€œwhat is on the other side of my comfort?â€
turning off the wisdom of my own body in search of having â€œthe experience,â€
.
how many times did i say yes
when in my throat, like a lump of metal, i wanted to say:
no.
no i wonâ€™t drink that.
no i wonâ€™t come over. 
no i wonâ€™t take off my pants.
no i wonâ€™t sleep with you.
no.
i didnâ€™t know the boundaries were crossed until i was already in the dark.
.
if i could only give my twenty year old self a sweet and safe embrace;
and whisper to her: â€œiâ€™ve got you.â€
.
what happened next?
i took responsibility.
fueled by the inquiry of: â€œwho am i?â€
i took a never ending journey inward to explore and reveal the deep crevices of my own mind and soul.
i blossomed and transformed, not always liking the layers that were revealed,
but i welcome them anyway.
i turned my pain into fuel; i turned my shame into growth; i turned my knowledge into wisdom.
and still, more healing remains.
.
what now?
i am here to serve as a catalyst for young women to learn themselves intimately, to become leaders of their lives so that unlike me, they donâ€™t say yes when in their hearts all they want to say is: no.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
things always get better. do you have a heart beat? are you breathing? that means that all of those times you thought you would never make it through, that things couldn't possibly get better, that it was finally the end... well it wasn't.
---
things did get better. you did survive. you made it! every time you think that you will not make it through this, think of all of the times you did!
you are a warrior. you are a survivor. nothing and no one can stop you except for you! you are powerful and capable of growing through anything life has to throw at you and come out gloriously on the other side! ---
i have been depressed, alone, suicidal, because i didn't think there was any other way to make this life any better. i'm here now to say that it was all worth it! is my life perfect? no. is my life easy? no. my life is beautiful with all of its flaws and strengths. my life is mine, and my struggles have lead me to my answered prayers. the moral of the story is, if i would have given up, if i would not have pushed through, i would not be experiencing this glorious life i live today! ğŸ–¤
...

text:
in 20 years, i could be in the same circumstances as dr. christine blasey ford. i could be the woman who has to stand up in front of the entire nation and accuse a man from high school of events that have happened to me. events that i will never and have never told a soul and few people were involved. events that if brought to the police at the time could have sent a classmate to legal repercussions. but the american rape culture is so skewed i never have reported it. i could be that woman that stands up and tells my story; the moments in my life that have changed who i am, how i act, what i react to and have distorted my reality for years about what is sexually acceptable. i would be dr. christine blasey ford mocked by the president and the confirmation of this individual would prove my story is worth nothing.

as a woman that daily deals with sexual harassment both in my personal life and in the workplace, tomorrows vote will change my perspective of how much politics needs to change. why are white male senators concerned for the the â€œwhite maleâ€ to be persecuted for being the accused when i have been the victim every day of my life for the last 10 years. my heart goes out to dr. christine blasey ford. her story is real. any person, female or male, who has been sexually attacked at a young age knows her story is true. 
change is coming. all i can say is make sure you are registered to vote for this upcoming election. idc if you vote right or left, as millennials, our voice deserves to be heard. #drford #metoo

text:
â€œitâ€™s okay to be happy. the only thing being upset changes is how much pain youâ€™re making yourself feel.â€ my inner guidance has been whispering this to me all week- especially this evening.
.
this week has been weird. in my life things are beautiful. i did meaningful readings this week. i met a new baby one of my soul sisters had recently. an employee i love came back to my company for the holidays. and so much more great stuff. things are really good.
.
but on wednesday during yoga there was a shooting outside the studio. we could hear it as we practiced. we could see flashing lights as we laid in shavasana. i saw ambulances pulling away, sirens blaring when i left. it didnâ€™t effect me personally. but i felt like i should feel bad about it because it happened, & i heard when it did.
.
today the senate made a decision that i feel is really detrimental to the future of our country. this is personal to everyone, including me. i worked hard to help hillary so this wouldnâ€™t happen. i worked hard for obama to build a foundation for our nationâ€™s future that feels like itâ€™s been crumbling before our eyes. i feel helpless to stop it from happening outside of casting my vote in november, & knocking on doors to encourage others to do the same.
.
so iâ€™ve been conflicted. my life right now is great. and yet all these of things happening around me- in my country & my city- are devastating. iâ€™ve been feeling guilty when iâ€™m happy & guilty when i smile.  i havenâ€™t known what itâ€™s okay to feel.
.
so i turned to god. and the answer i got was â€œbeing happy doesnâ€™t mean you donâ€™t care. itâ€™s okay to be happy. holding pain serves nobody. holding pain changes nothing.â€
.
iâ€™m choosing to witness & experience my emotions about todayâ€™s decisions by susan collins, jeff flake & joe manchin, and to let them go. to recognize that there are things i canâ€™t control.
.
iâ€™m trusting that itâ€™s okay to be happy. it doesnâ€™t mean i agree with whatâ€™s happening. it doesnâ€™t mean i donâ€™t care. it just means iâ€™m choosing not to let it control me since i have no control over it.
.
i think thatâ€™s fair.

text:
aloha dark-moon sleepies!
.
a lot of you are new so today, i'm just going to keep it simple and re-introduce myself with things you may not know about this witch.
.
1. i started learning about spirit, tarot, plant medicine, dream interp, feng shui, sound healing & astrology when i was 5. my grandmamas also taught me in depth about religions & mythology from norse to buddhism to catholicism & #wicca to give me a stronger foundation in my healing work. (no pressure, right? lol) i was 6 when i asked my scripture teacher about mary magdalene and why jesus wasn't portrayed as dark-skinned.
2. i read about 5 books a week & every mag/newspaper from the atlantic to gq to that's life & vanity fair.
3. i've studied shamanism, #breathwork, meditation, polynesian massage, counseling, cbt & 'bush healing' modalities everywhere from rural australia to peru to new york & ireland.
4. i've had 5 near-death experiences, from my train being bombed, to car attack. i wake up grateful.
5. i was diagnosed with severe chronic fatigue syndrome (including vision loss) & pcos & healed these through adhering to the moon cycle. it literally saved me from going onto a disability pension.
6. i am maori, with most of my spiritual teachers being #latinx or black women. politics & spirituality have always interceded- spiritual bypassing wasn't an option!
7. i have synesthesia which means my senses overlap - i see words/voices in colour & taste what i touch.
8. my dream was to write books that change people's lives. still is.
9. my "other work" has included emergency services, social services & media.
10. my skin is so sensitive that i wear clothes inside out, at home! but i'm obsessed with haute couture & could tell you the difference between a max mara & rodarte with my eyes closed. i froth on interior design & had a subscription to home beautiful magazine as a kid. 
11. i'm happiest eating mangoes, climbing trees, swimming & am good at fishing! 
13. i am a #metoo survivor & advocate.
12. i have a list of every piÃ±a colada i've ever had, ranked. from over 108 different cities around the world.
.
if you wonder what a "real witch" looks like- this is it! our diversity is what makes us powerful!

text:
â€œiâ€™m now a news anchor, and the #metoo movement gave me the strength to share my story of survival on live television,â€ says ali bradley who was drugged and raped at age 23 after coming to new york city for what she thought was a movie audition. â€œi was motivated by the idea that maybe my truth would help just one person understand they arenâ€™t alone and itâ€™s not their faultâ€”that there isnâ€™t anything they could have done differently,â€ she continues. â€œand if what i said resonated with one person, it was worth my digging up old memories and broadcasting them live.â€
.
the response she received was overwhelming in a beautiful way. â€œmessages poured in from complete strangers who shared their own truths with me, including one man in his late 60s who told me about the horrible assault he endured. he hadnâ€™t yet told his own family. his bravery was inspiring. i was so honored and humbled. since sharing my story, i have had more frequent flashbacks, but i work weekly with a therapist. my husband and family continue to support me, even when iâ€™m having a rough weekâ€”or month. sharing my story helped me transition from victim to survivor. to me, the difference is power. iâ€™m now in control of how i feel. i know what happened wasnâ€™t my fault.â€
.
here,Â bradley and 5 other sexual abuse survivorsÂ openÂ up toÂ @healthmagazineÂ about the personal experience thatÂ made them decideÂ to add their voices to the #metoo reckoning, and how thisÂ movement that continues to gain strength and powerÂ has transformed their lives.

text: #brucemckinnonâ€™s editorial cartoon resonated strongly with me. i was sexually assaulted for the first time when i was 17. i was on a date & i still remember what i wore; a pair of jeans and a red knit sweater. we were at his house watching a movie & we had gone into his bedroom. we were on his bed kissing & he wanted to put his hands down my pants. i didnâ€™t want him to, so i moved his hand away. he was more forceful in his attempt & he forced his hand down into my pants & penetrated me with his fingers. i told him to stop & tried to stop him, but he used his other hand to restrain me. he was much stronger than me. i clearly remember saying no repeatedly & him continuing to assault me & kiss me aggressively. he bit down hard on my bottom lip. i started to cry. i was scared & i felt helpless. he only stopped when a car horn honked in the driveway. it was my father there to pick me up, as my curfew was approaching. when he stopped, i got off the bed, wiped away my tears & tried to make myself look â€œpresentableâ€ before i saw my dad. my assaulter acted as if nothing happened, leaned in to kiss me goodnight & told me he would call me the next day. i walked to the car, trying my hardest to hold back my tears. my dad asked me how my night went & i said it went fine. it was not fine & i was not okay. i looked in the visor mirror & i saw my bottom lip starting to swell where he but me. we drove home in silence. i didnâ€™t tell my dad or mom. i didnâ€™t tell anyone. i was scared of what would happen. i didnâ€™t want anyone to know. i told myself â€œat least he didnâ€™t rape me.â€ if i told my parents, i was afraid they would be upset with me for being with a guy in his bedroom & putting myself in that situation. i blamed myself because i wanted him to kiss me, but i didnâ€™t want it to go any further. sadly my story is not unique. sexual assault is one of the most unreported crimes! text:
grew up, feelings dismissed: "everybody feels that. it's normal." like "oh, okay nevermind then." taught me to doubt myself. discount myself. discredit my feelings. not important unless it's unique. mm wait tho nothing is. good luck with that. don't learn to process your feelings. why even acknowledge em. it's useless, a hassle. no one cares enough to hear it.
-
14. no sense of self worth. set up with a boy i rated to a friend. we talked. felt special. called. kissed. loved. fucked. continued on in abuse for over 5 years. everytime almost lost it, almost felt too good to stay,  that doubt came in like a fucking anvil and crushed me back down to him: "you're overreacting, it's fine, everybody feels that. call him back."

text: we believed dr. anita hill 27 years ago. we believe dr. christine blasey ford now. i am proud to be one of 1600+ women united in the #webelieveher campaign. this â€œwe believe herâ€ campaign started as an effort to manifest fury into action. on september 25, 2018 we published a full page ad in @usatoday.  the next day, on september 26, 2018, phenomenal woman published their full page ad in the new york times with 1600 men believing dr. ford. using the medium of the newspaper was symbolic. in addition to the ads, we have paid for 3 mobile billboard trucks to be in d.c. today and tomorrow. these simple acts allowed us to reclaim our voices and harness the power of women united in support of each other, along with men who refuse to allow the deeply entrenched and toxic culture of misogyny to persist. we do this so that in 27 years, young women and men donâ€™t look back and wonder if nothing had changed at all. we do this to showcase a culture that silences survivors and elevates the accused. we do this so that one day more women are sitting on the senate judiciary committee on both sides. dear #senators, we believe her. so should you. find out more via www.webelieveher.us

text:
those of you who know me personally know that this has been a very difficult couple of weeks for me, given the news cycle and some painful experiences in my own life. i am very fortunate to know some strong, vivacious women and survivors, a network of support and access to a therapist. and i am fortunate for my insta folks who always have a cute piggie or doggie to make me forget my anxiety and flashbacks and panic for a moment every day. i love you and appreciate you all. if any of you are survivors and want someone to reach out to, i am here. i believe you. my friends believe you. and we'll be here, much like a sweet pig on your shoulder, to keep you warm and loved. always and no matter whatâ¤

text:
this is a poem about periods and politics and super powers.
in the meantime i will do what i always do.
i will bleed for five days straight.
i will not die.â€¨i will do the opposite, in fact.â€¨i will live and support others and thrive as i shed layer upon layer of old fears, old pain, the stems cells of old hopes. â€¨i'll bleed the fresh wounds out too. no sense holding my life's blood in, stopped up and congested, when there's so much work to be done.â€¨you see womxn know there is no wound you could deal us that we couldn't bleed out and go right on living.â€¨of course we might have to make a mess along the way, bright red blood staining white sheets like a rorschach test, telling the story of our rage and sorrow.â€¨i might frame mine next time and title it a monument to resilience. â€¨but mostly my blood is hidden, transmuting pain to a fresh hope for life right under your nose. to look at me you would not see the magic happen, but its there silently spinning the water wheel of renewal so that next time you will still find me standing in defiance, bled dry, refreshed and ready for the next cycle. â€¨so do what you need to do on capitol hill.â€¨just know we will bleed, we will keep bleeding.â€¨the streets of washington dc will be red rivers of our blood.â€¨you may drown,â€¨but we will not die.
#metoo #believewomen #believesurvivors #stopkavanaugh

text:

the battle will continue-we will never give up. we will use our power in the midterms. but right now i need ice cream, a vodka cocktail, comfort food, the peace pipe, some tender loving and giggles. in no particular order-though all at once would be rather delicious. 
today we rest and restore. we remind ourselves and each other that beauty, goodness and light still exist. 
in the coming days we will begin to strategize the fight ahead.

if youâ€™ve never been sexually assaulted, maybe you should not try to assume you know what you would do if you had been. maybe you shouldnâ€™t try to insinuate that it could have been avoided. maybe you shouldnâ€™t even question whether or not it actually happened. maybe you shouldnâ€™t pose the idea, that the rapist didnâ€™t know the sexual act was not consensual. maybe, idkğŸ¤·ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸.
all of these things add on to the shame and embarrassment that we already feel so deeply. this week has been triggering to say the least. every single comment along the lines of, â€œanyone can claim theyâ€™ve been raped....why didnâ€™t she tell someone when it happened...well she was drunk...â€ etc., has been a trigger. not to mention the presidentâ€™s reaction to the case, along with all of the other republicans voting yes.
iâ€™ve actually never spoken about being assaulted until yesterday. and i thank every single woman who spoke out and told their story. other people might question why we are speaking, they might even accuse us of being dramatic, or attention seeking. but the truth is, this week is going to change the way people perceive and handle the topic of rape. iâ€™m sure of it. and itâ€™s no thanks to the president of the united states, thatâ€™s for sure. itâ€™s thanks to dr. ford, and every single woman who came forward to tell their story. itâ€™s no thanks to the men and women who question the validity of each case. itâ€™s thanks to the men and women who stand in support.
this week will change history, even if it only means that victims will feel comfortable and supported enough, to come forward at the time of their assault. and for all the women who didnâ€™t come forward at the time of their assault, maybe theyâ€™ll feel a little more comfortable to seek the help they need to heal, even if itâ€™s a little late.
while speaking out about our assaults is key to the evolution of our society, it also help us work through our suppressed, oppressed and repressed traumas.

text:
dunia (@duniabadawi) shares her experiences as an immigrant and struggles accepting her identity and own culture while living in a new one. âœ¨
â€¢
â€¢
â€œi used to hate the word immigrant. it embodied everything that i hated about myself, everything that others made me hate. i hated that i didnâ€™t understand the culture or why i wasnâ€™t â€œbeautifulâ€ enough to be a part of it. i hated that my parents spoke broken english and i never seemed to be able to pronounce my words properly. i hated my â€œarab noseâ€ which always seemed too big for my face, but what does that mean anyways? 
i hated my curls and the fact that everyone loved comparing them to poodle fur. i hated it so much that i tried every chemical and flat iron to â€œfixâ€ the issue that was never even there, and only ended up damaging my hair for good. i hated my oily skin and my body, which was never â€œskinnyâ€ enough. but i should have never been ashamed of any of this. ashamed enough to drive myself to 72 pounds before realizing that iâ€™m on the verge of completely losing myself, literally. 
but i wanted to be that ideal of beauty, the girl with the soft silky hair and perfect skin. with the â€œproportionateâ€ features and skinny body that i didnâ€™t even have to work for. but most of all i hated the fact that i let others effect me to the point of wanting to hate my own heritage and destroy everything that made me who i am.  iâ€™m not going to lie and say that iâ€™m completely happy with who i am, i still catch myself glancing in the mirror and hating the reflection. but itâ€™s a process and iâ€™m a lot better than i once was. and at least now when i smile, itâ€™s pure.â€ #ourwomensvoices

text: sisters, many of us are feeling traumatized and re-traumatized right now. if we may suggest, belleruth naparstek's healing trauma guided imagery . . . "with a soft touch on your shoulder, your guide invites you to come along so that together you can explore your broken heart...the gentlest invitation, if you are willing...." "you are making your way through crumpled piles of shattered dreams, ragged heaps of lost innocence and your guide is at your side, comforting and encouraging you to continue... gently pointing out crust outcroppings of old guilt and self-blame..." "you can't make this place go away, but your courage in exploring it will change it in time...." "noticing a golden light up from the ground some distance away and walking towards it, you slowly approach what looks to be a glowing cave or hollow...you see this is a tunnel...leading down into an older, deeper part of your heart....aware that somehow this place if familiar to you, you know this place, and slowly you remember this is your oldest home...." <3

text:
#day5 â€œhe/she is not abusive.  i mean, they choked me, but they didnâ€™t hit me so...â€
.
comments like this are no surprise to advocates, first responders, medical teams or law enforcement and unfortunately are more common than you might think. choking aka strangulation is abuse and in many states considered a felony.  here are some quick facts you should know (via www.thehotline.org)
.
strangulation is a significant predictor for future lethal violence
.
if your partner has strangled you in the past, your risk of being killed by them is 10 times higher
.
strangulation is one of the most lethal forms of domestic violence: unconsciousness may occur within seconds and death within minutes.
