text:
i'm livid in general - but i think what has made me most angry is the absolute dismissal of women and victims who are trying to make their voices heard.  being waved away, being told to "grow up", being told they are "bullying" senators (collins) - this is garbage.  it's ugly garbage, and should be denounced.  i'm filled with such fury, because i know victims.  i have been a victim.  when they dismiss these women, when they dismiss dr. ford - when you dismiss them, you dismiss me.  you dismiss women and victims that i love with all my heart.  this is shameful and audacious behavior, and it is a deal breaker for me.

text:
iâ€™m having a difficult time being vocal online about sexual assault these days, even though i have so much to say on the topic. i want to be loud. i want to be brave. i tell all of you to use your words and voices, but iâ€™m finding it hard to follow my own advice.
.
instead, iâ€™ve been doing what i always do when iâ€™m sad/angry: iâ€™m writing. iâ€™m writing tweets i donâ€™t send, blog posts i donâ€™t share, and filling my journal.
.
today, to get my mind off the news, i opened mail from my readers. rather than writing for myself, i figured it would be a good day to write back to you. this was the last letter i opened. and iâ€™m in tears again, for her and for everyone else who has a story like this.
.
like this reader, my mom was the only person i told. it was one of the hardest things iâ€™ve ever had to do. i expected her to say it was no big deal or that i was overreacting. but she didnâ€™t. she believed me immediately and took action without hesitating, and iâ€™ll never have enough words to thank her for that.
.
writing that scene in little do we know was my way of honoring her. my way of thanking her and all the other moms and trusted adults who didnâ€™t dismiss the girls who came to them broken, scared, and blaming themselves.
.
it happened over 25 years ago. in this book, i intentionally used the exact words he said to me, because i never forgot them. i remember other things too. what i was wearing. the sound in the room. running to the bathroom, locking the door, crying and shaking and wondering how i was ever going to get out of there. to this day, i canâ€™t tell you how i got out of that bathroom, but clearly i did.
.
i wanted to write this book because i knew it would help me heal, but mostly, because i hoped it might help others feel seen, understood, and less alone. and today, on the day i needed it most, i hear that it did that for at least one person. that means everything to me.
.
believe women. believe your daughters and sisters and friends. believe them.
.
iâ€™m off to write a long letter to this reader to thank her for sharing her story, and for inspiring me to write and actually post this. bravery is, indeed, contagious.
.
love to all of you.

text:
the museum of african-american history and culture is in part a catalog of cruelty. amid all the stories of perseverance, tragedy, and unlikely triumph are the artifacts of inhumanity and barbarism: the child-size slave shackles, the bright red robes of the wizards of the ku klux klan, the recordings of civil-rights protesters being brutalized by police.

the artifacts that persist in my memory, the way a bright flash does when you close your eyes, are the photographs of lynchings. but itâ€™s not the burned, mutilated bodies that stick with me. itâ€™s the faces of the white men in the crowd. thereâ€™s the photo of the lynching of thomas shipp and abram smith in indiana in 1930, in which a white man can be seen grinning at the camera as he tenderly holds the hand of his wife or girlfriend. thereâ€™s the undated photo from duluth, minnesota, in which grinning white men stand next to the mutilated, half-naked bodies of two men lashed to a post in the streetâ€”one of the white men is straining to get into the picture, his smile cutting from ear to ear. thereâ€™s the photo of a crowd of white men huddled behind the smoldering corpse of a man burned to death; one of them is wearing a smart suit, a fedora hat, and a bright smile.

their names have mostly been lost to time. but these grinning men were someoneâ€™s brother, son, husband, father. they were human beings, people who took immense pleasure in the utter cruelty of torturing others to deathâ€”and were so proud of doing so that they posed for photographs with their handiwork, jostling to ensure they caught the eye of the lens, so that the world would know theyâ€™d been there. their cruelty made them feel good, it made them feel proud, it made them feel happy. and it made them feel closer to one another.

#feminism

text: the undecided votes on the kavanugh nomination came into fruition on fridays procedural hearing as senators reviewed the week-long investigation conducted by the fbi into allegations of sexual misconduct by nominee brett kavanaugh. republican lawmakers claimed the report exonerated the judge from any wrongdoing giving them the go ahead to confirm the judge into the supreme court. however, democrats refuted republicans, asserting that the scope of the investigation was too limited. the fbi interviewed 9 people in total with notable accusee julia swetnick left off the fbiâ€™s radar. the confirmation needs at least 50 votes with vice president mike pence holding the tie-breaking vote. republicans currently hold a 51-49 majority in the senate which means they can only lose one republican vote- r-lisa murkowski. r-montana steve daines will be attending his daughters wedding on saturday, further complicating the republicans efforts to confirm kavanaugh. with d-west virginia joe manchin agreeing to confirm kavanaugh, daines vote may not be needed. senators are stuck between a rock and a hard place with mid-term election politics looming as they seek re-election and the cultural domination of the #metoo movement igniting constituents into action. now that the needed votes to confirm kavanaugh have solidified itâ€™ll be interesting to see how the final confirmation vote holds up on saturday...

matching a fancy bathroom at a fancy store with upmarket shopping bags that arenâ€™t mine. last weekâ€™s brunch and shopping trip with my girls v and a. itâ€™s always nice when your buds are amenable to shooting indulgent portraits of you, even though they laugh, knowing how freakinâ€™ silly it all is. i mean, a girlâ€™s gotta get her outfit shots somehow, amirite?
â€“
i post this now because it reminds me of a happy day instead of everything going down in our world at the moment.
â€“
this weekâ€™s been crap. a multiple sexual assault accused judge has all but been confirmed as the next surpeme court judge, potentially endangering womenâ€™s, people of color, and lgbtqia rights that have been painfully fought for over the last several generations.
-
as a survivor of two (not just one!)sexual assaults, i am horrified. this whole process has brought up severe anxiety, symptoms of ptsd, and memories of those horrific events of 2004. i am severely disappointed in the senate. even if he was completely innocent, just the scandal surrounding him alone should disqualify him. and his performance during the hearingâ€”the rampant high school drinking and sex gamesâ€”was horrendous. his testimony exhibited clearly that he lacks the calm, non-emotional, balanced, and non-partisan, mental clarity and temperament a scotus justice requires. his presence in the highest court denigrates the court and for all it stands. itâ€™s a disappointing time for this country. sometimes i wonder what life would be like if i were not born a female of color, but a wealthy white male.

text:
how to create order out of chaos

hey there!

feeling some chaos from your ptsd?

yup, i've been thereâ€¦

my home life was in chaosâ€¦

between me and my loved ones, we'd get into screaming matches, and put holes in walls.

my health was in chaosâ€¦

i would only eat pop tarts (my all time low was fluff, on bread, topped with sprinkles), and i had no exercise routine whatsoever.

my personal life was in chaosâ€¦

my home, my car, my finances, my career, were messy, and all over the place.

and, my emotional life was in chaosâ€¦enough said about that.

here's what i did to bring in some orderâ€¦

i started dividing the parts of my life upâ€¦

health, wealth, relationships, love, family, etcâ€¦

i took out a piece of paper and took a deep and honest look at each area and rated them on a scale from 1 to 10 how well i was doingâ€¦

i nearly got 1's in almost everything.

but, it was important to know where i was starting, without judgement.

i then started to take action to make each area better.
i made a plan and stuck to it.

and, guess what?

things didn't get betterâ€¦.right away.

but, i chipped away at things, and a few of my 1's started to turn into 2's, and things got better and better.

i kept an eye on how i was doing and was always looking to get better in each area.

i wasn't looking to go from a 1 to a 10 in a week, i was looking for incremental improvements, and was celebrating my progress and my success.

if you rate your life at all 1's that's okay.

you need to focus on improving each area consistently until you've got them all rocking and rolling at 10's across the board.

interested in how i went from all 1's to all 10's?

i show you *exactly* how to do it in this free training.

begin your journey to all 10's now by clicking the link in my bio.. to your recovery!

hope you have a great friday! - kayleen

text:
as an enneagram 9, i generally try to stay out of things, and i shrink away during any tense conversations. i admittedly don't pay as much attention to world events as i probably should, and sometimes i feel too far behind to even catch up anyway.
.
but these past couple weeks have been a bit of a turning point for me in regards to women. i had to ask a friend to catch me up on this whole kavanaugh situation and once i understood what was going on, and read countless women's stories, i felt a fire start to burn within me.
.
there is a lot of pain out there. and it almost overwhelmed me to the point of hopelessness. last friday, i found myself feeling incredibly worthless, anxious and depressed. and i haven't been assaulted. i've just had the regular things that most women experience at one point or another but simply chalk up to the experience of being a woman: being grabbed, called at, joked about, or feeling fear simply while walking to the car or encountering a man. if i felt how i felt,  i can't imagine what one must feel who has been assaulted.
.
but women have inspired me. there are so many incredibly strong women out there. and so many powerful voices that are paving the way for me. there is a fire starting to burn in my heart to fight harder for women. to get educated. to fight for a better world for my daughters. to start a fire in their hearts too.
.
and to teach my sons well.
.
#blackfridays

.

text:
everyone has their own body, everyone has their own brain
everyone thinks a little differently, no one is exactly the same. 
and because our body belongs only to us
we get to decide who is - and who is not - allowed to touch.
you set your own boundaries and you decide what goes too far
your boundaries wonâ€™t be identical to what everyone elseâ€™s are.
what makes you feel uncomfortable, may not be the same for a friend
and you should never change your boundaries, in an attempt to fit in. 
giving someone your permission, is what it means to give consent
and if you say no to someone, it is not an argument. 
if someone crosses your boundaries, use your voice as a powerful tool
tell a person you trust that someone violated your rules.
whatever happens, never let your voice be taken away 
donâ€™t get lost in the silence of the words you want to say.
every day things happen, and those become the stories you write
focus with resilience on the magical moments in your life.
know not all moments are magic and some moments can be bad.
but even within your worst moments â€“ there are lessons to be had.
every story you write wonâ€™t make you feel like a powerful girl
and certainly not all stories you will want shared with the world.
powerful people may try to make you feel embarrassed or afraid
but be a silence breaker â€“tell your worst stories anyway.
you change the world, uniting and supporting women alike
by believing every girlâ€™s truth and joining them in our fight. 
you see, the way stories work, theyâ€™ll be bad guys and heroes too
but if a story lacks a hero â€“ then make sure the hero is you.

text:
17-year-old ohio teen murdered after escalating abuse from 28-year-old boyfriend
â€”
lâ€™union suite fam, i know that this little girl was not haitian, but she was part of the black community, and domestic violence is a big issue in our haitian community as well, so i think we might want to post about her:
â€”
17yr-old lashonda childs had a job, owned a business, looked after her family, and went back to school to continue her education. she was beautiful and vivacious, but, just two days shy of her 18th birthday, she was murdered by a 28yr-old man who would not take "no" for an answer.
â€”
no matter the gender, if someone saysâ€”or showsâ€”that they do not want to sleep with you, date you, see you or communicate with you, your next move needs to be to respect that and move on. no one owes themselves to us.
â€”
it is important that we recognize that domestic violence is at an epidemic level not only the haitian community, but in the broader black community worldwide. no one deserves to die in this manner, and no family deserves this degree of suffering. the level of entitlement in men who canâ€™t accept a "no" is sickening. check on your friends and check your problematic friends.
â€”
lâ€™union suite blogger: maco m. (@macomonthervil)
â€”

text:
real z news: susan collins just spent the last 50 minutes praising brett kavanagh and his judicial record. she talked about her "outrage that allegations of sexual assault could even make it into the confirmation process." she said that although she believes christine blasey ford was assaulted at some time, her allegations failed to meet a standard of proof and cannot prevent kavanagh from being appointed to the supreme court. she did not mention the other women who also accused kavanagh of different levels of sexual assault, and she didn't mention brett kavanagh's blatantly partisan behavior during his judiciary hearing. she then told the senate and the country that she will vote yes tomorrow to confirm brett kavanagh to the supreme court. it is now a done deal. tomorrow, accused sexual predator, brett kavanagh, will become the swing vote on the united states supreme court. make no mistake, the supplemental investigation into allegations of sexual assault against brett kavanagh, was a sham conducted for the sole purpose of making it look like they even considered allegations of sexual assault as a disqualifier for a lifetime appointment on the highest court in the land, which clearly they do not! jeff flake is voting yes and so are democratic senator joe manchin, and all the other supposed undecided senators with the exception of lisa murkowski, who voted no on the cloture vote today and is expected to vote no again tomorrow on the actual vote to confirm.

#metoo #whyididntreport #michaelavenatti #presidentobama #barakobama #basta #impeachtrump2019 #democracy #america #notthedumbfuckwhisperer #impeachtrump #nowthis #blacklivesmatter #dumptrump #nevertrump #hillaryclinton #truth #imissobamaalready #liberals #occupydemocrats #imstillwithher #lovetrumpshate #berniesanders #imissobama #donaldtrump #trump

text:
happy friday friends!
.
you may have noticed iâ€™ve been absent on the socials this week. thereâ€™s a lot of big things happening in the pp world lately, while the things going on in the world outside have been nothing short of plain scary. iâ€™ve found it almost impossible to focus on work while my heart aches and breaks daily for every survivor out there watching the so called leaders of our nation, and those who support them, turn their backs. so iâ€™ve had to step away for a moment. i know that each and every one of us are fighters and survivors. we will not give up and we will not go away. we will fight harder and stronger to give our young women and children a future full of hope, equality and justice. for me, this means building something that will outlast this administration. something inspiring that will bring hope and joy into our lives when the outside world seems so dark. and when it all seems too much to bare, remember, we are the women, men, sons and daughters of this nation that will never stop fighting for what is right. and that alone is cause for celebration. so iâ€™ll see you all tomorrow, for a new day, and a new reason to celebrate. â¤ï¸

text: if you listen to partisan rhetoric. if you take in skewed points of view. if you listen to pundits or people who are scared of this future or that future. you hear a fearful tone emerge from the chatter. as a writer i see these stories coming to life. i wonder if these people are right or just fear mongering for the base of their beliefs? what could the future actually hold? are we paving a new way for lovers to engage? is it destined to become just another bureaucracy of government. a new way to manage our lives? an institution built on fear. are the violators the future outlaws? can a kiss on the spot land you in jail? blacklist you from your children? make you liable in ways never before imagined? i see the need for change. i understand why this conversation needs to take place. i know the value of truth and the love that it brings. but is it our nature as human beings to take things to the extreme? or is that just white noise from a passing generation that wishes to keep things as they are? instead of how they should be? i wrote this with the extreme in mind. but i hope that we as a majority of good minded people are wise enough to know the difference between what needs to be discussed and what we can do as a whole to ensure a future that is both spontaneous and safe. thanks for reading. i invite your comments. but please be respectful to me and others when you do. thanks again!! ğŸ¤”â¤ğŸ˜Š #conversations #future #fiction #metoo

text:
i had a distance reiki session w/ a client this week, where the dark goddess came in a shamanic healing vision i had while channeling the reiki. she stayed with me so long after that i needed to paint her. this is also an excerpt from my first book & i had forgotten that she had once come to me in word channeling before.. seeing her in a vision was really electric.! she was a skeleton woman in a black cape with a shovel digging my client out of the earth. i was a bit taken aback but my reiki guide, said , "sherry, it's okay trust let her do her work, you know very well you cannot get to the light without passing through the dark" at one point in the vision she looked at me and she said, "most don't know what it means to be feminine. to be feminine means to be stripped to the bones" . this goddess is all about truth, stripping you bare, resurrecting you. she's ferile, intense, minces no words. my client is in a place of deep desire to live her feminine energy, and so she came in for her, because she knows she is ready. so beautiful! this session was full of mystic transformative energy. so much happened,  came through... i was a bit drained after channeling it but the next day i woke up with a boundless energy. i felt scoured and alive! . by the way we need this fierce dark goddess potent energy on this planet now more than ever so that the feminine can be seen and heard valued and rise!!!
.
.
 interested in my books, art, distance reiki & oracle guidance readings? ..and your own soul journey? links in bio. or pm me. (my etsy shop is closed for a bit  right now so if you're interested in the book i can send it to you directly just send me a pm. )
.
.
